## History and use

[Exeter Cathedral Astronomical Clock](/Exeter_Cathedral_Astronomical_Clock), showing the double-XII numbering scheme.
World War II RAF [sector clock](/Sector_clock) that can be read either in 12- or 24-hour notation.

The natural day-and-night division of a calendar day forms the fundamental basis as to why each day is split into two cycles. Originally there were two cycles: one cycle which could be tracked by the position of the Sun (day), followed by one cycle which could be tracked by the Moon and stars (night). This eventually evolved into the two 12-hour periods which are used today, one called "a.m." starting at midnight and another called "p.m." starting at noon.

The 12-hour clock can be traced back as far as [Mesopotamia](/Mesopotamia) and [ancient Egypt](/Ancient_Egypt). Both an Egyptian [sundial](/Sundial) for daytime use and an Egyptian [water clock](/Water_clock) for night-time use were found in the tomb of Pharaoh [Amenhotep I](/Amenhotep_I). Dating to c. 1500 BC, these clocks divided their respective times of use into 12 hours each.

The [ancient Romans](/Ancient_Rome) also [used a 12-hour clock](/Roman_timekeeping): daylight and nighttime were each divided into 12 equal intervals (of varying duration according to the season). The nighttime hours were grouped into four [watches](/Watchkeeping) (vigiliae).

The first mechanical clocks in the 14th century, if they had dials at all, showed all 24 hours using the [24-hour analog dial](/24-hour_analog_dial), influenced by astronomers' familiarity with the [astrolabe](/Astrolabe) and sundial and by their desire to model the [Earth's apparent motion around the Sun](/Earth%27s_rotation). In [Northern Europe](/Northern_Europe) these dials generally used the 12-hour [numbering scheme](/Numbering_scheme) in [Roman numerals](/Roman_numerals) but showed both a.m. and p.m. periods in sequence. This is known as the double-XII system and can be seen on many surviving clock faces, such as those at [Wells](/Wells_Cathedral_clock) and [Exeter](/Exeter_Cathedral).

Elsewhere in Europe, numbering was more likely to be based on the 24-hour system (I to XXIV). The 12-hour clock was used throughout the [British Empire](/British_Empire).

During the 15th and 16th centuries, the 12-hour analog dial and time system gradually became established as standard throughout Northern Europe for general public use. The 24-hour analog dial was reserved for more specialized applications, such as [astronomical clocks](/Astronomical_clock) and chronometers.

Most analog clocks and watches today use the 12-hour dial, on which the shorter hour hand rotates once every 12 hours and twice in one day. Some analog clock dials have an inner ring of numbers along with the standard 1-to-12 numbered ring. The number 12 is paired either with a 00 or a 24, while the numbers 1 through 11 are paired with the numbers 13 through 23, respectively. This modification allows the clock to also be read in [24-hour notation](/24-hour_notation). This kind of 12-hour clock can be found in countries where the 24-hour clock is preferred.

## Use by country

